Supplementary Figures

Increased pollination generalization does not necessarily result in relaxed evolutionary constraints on corolla shape

Simon Joly, François Lambert, Hermine Alexandre, Julien Clavel, Étienne Léveillé-Bourret, John L. Clark

Submitted to The American Naturalist

Supplementary Figure 1

Species phylogeny showing mean corolla shapes (after Procrustes analysis). Pollination syndromes are shown with those that have been confirmed indicated by a black contour. Pie charts represent the joint probability of each state at corresponding nodes as estimated by stochastic mapping from all species, including those with syndromes inferred from their flower shape. Clade posterior probabilities are shown above branches. Outgroup taxa are not shown.

Supplementary Figure 2

Principal component analysis showing the corolla shape morphospace for all individuals. Pollination syndromes are shown by different colours. The large dots on the plot represent the species means and the individual floral shapes (small dots) are associated with their species mean by gray lines. Place your cursor over the points to get species and specimen information. You can also zoom in the figure.

Supplementary Figure 3

Principal component analysis showing the corolla shape morphospace for the individuals excluding the hummingbird pollinated species. Pollination syndromes are shown by different colours. The large dots on the plot represent the species means and the individual floral shapes (small dots) are associated with their species mean by gray lines. Place your cursor over the points to get species and specimen information. You can also zoom in the figure.

Supplementary Figure 4

Akaike (\(AICc\)) weights for the multivariate evolutionary models when all species are included in the analyses (syndromes are inferred from the corolla shape for unknown).

Figures generated with R with the libraries plotly ggplot2, and knitr.
